reviewText:
Hope this will help other gamers and platform enthusiasts, have fun! ^.^

Type:Rider is a neat..let's call it documentary game, where the story consists of the history of writing and its evolution, you are 2 random balls that can jump and go to find out about diferent key moments in the history of writing. even if you're not curious about history (sorry for repeating history so much), the game is challenging and fun to do;

Cons:
- not very challenging;
- replayability is almost none existent because you can clear the game in 1 try, secret level is quite hard though;
- short game;

Pros:
- you can learn new interesting things while you play a game (that's rare);
- all the level's are quite creative, original and variate;
- each level has it's own theme and graphic wise it's pleasantly looking;
- most achievements are easy to do;
- short game;

Beautiful, but sometimes irritating platformer…

It’s about: exploring the history of alphabet, fonts and typographic industry;
jumping.
Why you should play this: it offers nice graphic and 10 levels (including introduction and bonus) with unique style: each one describes new period of typographic history and contains 4 stages (last stage usually presented with easy puzzle);
it includes interactive books with description of most important persons and events in typographic history (you have to collect asterisks to obtain all information);
on some levels it refers to old classic games (like Pong, Tetris);
you like platformers and don’t mind to read something interesting and educational.
Why you may not like it: you might spend some time to get used to physics of that “two-spot” you have to control;
on some levels it can really ♥♥♥♥♥♥ you off so much that you will just start thinking ”Dammit, somebody, please, return these ♥♥♥♥ing “balls” to someone who lost it!”;
you are pretty sure that playing and reading must be two different, unconnected processes.
It’s a bundle game – it’s foolishly to demand from it something marvelous or majestic for such price.
